1 (18) Adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to establish fees that are
2 necessary for the administration of this chapter, including costs of
3 inspections, analysis, and publications.
4 (19) Adopt rules under IC 4-22-2 to establish civil fines for the
5 following:
6 (A) Failure to submit a report required under this chapter.
7 (B) Failure to pay a fee required under this chapter.
8 (c) The seed commissioner, in response to an application for the
9 issuance of a special use permit under subsection (b)(17), may:
10 (1) issue a special use permit;
11 (2) issue a special use permit subject to conditions; or
12 (3) deny a special use permit request.
13 In determining whether to issue a special use permit, the seed
14 commissioner shall consider each species of prohibited noxious weed
15 or restricted noxious weed separately. The seed commissioner may
16 revoke a special use permit at any time if it appears that the permit
17 holder is not complying with the conditions established under the
18 special use permit.
19 SECTION 10. IC 15-15-1-28, AS AMENDED BY P.L.143-2024,
20 SECTION 1, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
21 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 28. (a) The state seed commissioner may by rule
22 define seed labeling and testing terms in common usage such as "pure
23 seed" and "germination".
24 (b) A rule adopted by the state seed commissioner under this section
25 must be based on published sources such as the rules of the Association
26 of Official Seed Analysts.
27 (c) The state seed commissioner shall apply the agricultural seed
28 and vegetable seed standards set forth in 7 CFR 201 as the state
29 germination standards and requirements for agricultural seed and
30 vegetable seed.
31 (d) The state seed commissioner shall use:
32 (1) the terms used in seed testing and labeling; and
33 (2) the methods of testing for official samples;
34 as provided in the Association of Official Seed Analysts, Rules for
35 Testing Seeds.
36 SECTION 11. IC 15-15-1-29, AS ADDED BY P.L.2-2008,
37 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
38 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 29. (a) If any kind and variety of seed present
39 in excess of five percent (5%) is "hybrid" seed, the seed must be
40 designated "hybrid" on the label.
41 (b) The percentage that is hybrid seed must be at least
42 ninety-five percent (95%) of the percentage of pure seed shown
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

6
1 unless the percentage of pure seed which is hybrid seed is shown
2 separately. If two (2) or more kinds or varieties are present in
3 excess of five percent (5%), each that is hybrid must be designated
4 as hybrid on the label.
5 (c) Any kind and variety that has pure seed which is less than
6 ninety-five percent (95%) but more than seventy-five percent
7 (75%) hybrid seed as a result of incompletely controlled pollination
8 in a cross must be labeled to show the percentage of pure seed that
9 is hybrid seed.
10 (d) One (1) kind and variety of seed may not be labeled as
11 hybrid if the pure seed contains less than seventy-five percent
12 (75%) hybrid seed. However, the seed may be labeled as a mixture
13 or blend.
14 (e) The state seed commissioner may, by rule, define controlled
15 conditions and satisfactory purity for the production of hybrid seed of
16 any kind. A hybrid designation shall must be treated as a variety name.
