12 SECTION 18. IC 15-15-1-33.2 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
13 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
14 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 33.2. (a) The name of a kind and
15 variety of seed and any descriptive terms pertaining to the seed
16 must be correctly represented in any labeling and advertisement
17 of the seed.
18 (b) The label for agricultural seed and vegetable seed must
19 contain the required information, in any form, that is clearly
20 legible and complies with this chapter and any rules adopted under
21 this chapter. The required information may be on a tag attached
22 securely to the container or printed in a conspicuous manner on a
23 side or the top of the container.
24 (c) The label may contain information in addition to that
25 required by this chapter if the additional information is not
26 misleading.
27 SECTION 19. IC 15-15-1-33.4 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
28 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
29 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 33.4. (a) Except as provided in
30 subsection (b), the name of each kind of agricultural seed or
31 vegetable seed is the name associated with one (1) or more related
32 species or subspecies which singly or collectively are:
33 (1) allowed under 7 CFR 201.34; or
34 (2) known by one (1) common name.
35 (b) A name of a kind of agricultural seed or vegetable seed that
36 is synonymous through broad common usage may be substituted
37 for the name in subsection (a) if the name:
38 (1) does not apply to more than one (1) kind of seed; and
39 (2) is not misleading.
40 (c) The representation of the same kind and variety of
41 agricultural seed or vegetable seed in any advertisement or
42 labeling must be confined to the kind and variety as determined
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

13
1 under this chapter. The kind name and variety name may not be
2 associated with words or terms that create a misleading impression
3 as to the history or characteristics of the kind and variety.
4 Descriptive terms and firm names may be used in kind and variety
5 names if the descriptive terms or firm names are a part of the
6 name of the kind and variety name of the seed. Examples:
7 Stringless Green Pod, Detroit Dark Red, Black Seeded Simpson,
8 and Henderson Bush Lima.
9 (d) A term that describes color, shape, size, habit of growth,
10 disease resistance, or other characteristics of the kind and variety
11 may be associated with the name of the kind and variety if it is
12 done in a manner that clearly indicates the descriptive term is not
13 a part of the name of the kind and variety. Examples: Oshkosh
14 Pepper (yellow), Copenhagen Market (round head) Cabbage, and
15 Kentucky Wonder pole bean.
16 (e) A term that describes the:
17 (1) quality;
18 (2) origin; or
19 (3) basis for representations made;
20 may be associated with the name of the kind and variety of seed, if
21 the term is clearly identified as being other than part of the name
22 of the kind and variety. Examples: Blue Tag Gem Barley, Idaho
23 Origin Alfalfa, and Grower's Affidavit of Variety Atlas Sorghum.
24 (f) A descriptive term that describes the manner or method of
25 production or conditioning of seed may be associated with the
26 name of the kind and variety of seed if the term is not misleading.
27 For example, the terms "certified", "registered", "scarified",
28 "treated", and "hulled" may be used if they are not misleading.
29 (g) A brand name or term taken from a trademark may be
30 associated with the kind and variety or mixtures of kinds or
31 varieties or blends of varieties of seed as an indication of the
32 source. However, the term must clearly indicate that the term is
33 not part of the name of the kind and variety, mixture, or blend.
34 Example: Ox Brand Golden Cross sweet corn. A brand name or
35 trademark may not be used in place of a variety name or in any
36 manner that may be interpreted as being a variety name.
37 SECTION 20. IC 15-15-1-33.6 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
38 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
39 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 33.6. (a) When both a brand and
40 variety name are stated, the following terms must be shown on the
41 seed label in the following order from left to right or top to bottom:
42 (1) The brand name.
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

14
1 (2) The word "brand".
2 (3) The variety name.
3 (4) The kind name.
4 (b) When a brand name is stated but no variety name is stated,
5 the following terms must be shown on the seed label in the
6 following order from left to right or top to bottom:
7 (1) The brand name.
8 (2) The word "brand".
9 (3) The kind name.
10 (4) The words "variety not stated".
11 SECTION 21. IC 15-15-1-33.8 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
12 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
13 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 33.8. (a) A seed mixture
14 consisting of two (2) or more varieties of the same kind may be
15 designated as a "blend" of seed if the following conditions are met:
16 (1) The word "blend" is included on the label as a part of the
17 name of the blend.
18 (2) The variety name of each component of a blend is shown
19 on the label along with the following information for each
20 component:
21 (A) The percentage by weight of each component in excess
22 of five percent (5%).
23 (B) The germination percentage.
24 (C) The hard seed percentage, if applicable.
25 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a)(2), the following information
26 may be placed on the label:
27 (1) The:
28 (A) variety designation of each component;
29 (B) percentage by weight of each component;
30 (C) germination percentage; and
31 (D) hard seed percentage, if applicable;
32 of each component may be omitted if the label states the kind
33 of seed and the words "varieties not stated".
34 (2) The blend may be represented by:
35 (A) one (1) common pure seed percentage;
36 (B) one (1) germination percentage; and
37 (C) one (1) hard seed percentage, if applicable;
38 for the blend as a whole.
39 (c) A blend or mixture may be assigned a brand name but not
40 a variety name.
41 (d) The labeling and advertisement of a varietal blend may not
42 imply that the seed is a single variety.
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

15
1 SECTION 22. IC 15-15-1-34, AS AMENDED BY P.L.10-2022,
2 SECTION 2, AND P.L.33-2022, SECTION 2, IS AMENDED TO
3 READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 34. (a) A
4 person who distributes agricultural seed or vegetable seed in Indiana
5 may apply to the state seed commissioner for a permit to use the
6 person's own labeling, report the quantity of seed sold, and pay the
7 inspection fee on the basis of the report.
8 (b) In making application for a permit under subsection (a), the
9 distributor must agree to the following:
10 (1) Label the seed with the information required by law.
11 (2) Keep the records the state seed commissioner considers
12 necessary to indicate accurately the number and size of containers
13 of each kind of agricultural seed and vegetable seed distributed
14 and the quantity of such seed distributed in bulk.
15 (3) Grant the state seed commissioner or the state seed
16 commissioner's authorized representative permission to examine
17 the records described in subdivision (2) and verify the statement
18 of quantity of seed distributed.
19 (4) Report under oath to the state seed commissioner on forms
20 furnished by the state seed commissioner the quantity of
21 agricultural seed and vegetable seed sold during the period
22 covered.
23 (c) The state seed commissioner may grant a permit under
24 subsection (a) if the state seed commissioner determines that the
25 applicant's proposed report of the quality of agricultural seed and
26 vegetable seed sold will lead to efficient enforcement of this chapter.
27 The state seed commissioner may revoke the permit at any time if it
28 appears to the state seed commissioner that the distributor is not
29 complying with the agreement described in subsection (b) or this
30 chapter. If:
31 (1) the report is not filed and the inspection fee not paid before
32 ten (10) days following the due date;
33 (2) the report of volume is false; or
34 (3) the labeling requirements of this chapter have not been
35 complied with;
36 the state seed commissioner may revoke the permit. If the inspection
37 fee is unpaid after the ten (10) day grace period, a penalty shall be
38 assessed in the amount of ten percent (10%) in addition to the amount
39 due.
40 (d) The report of quantity sold required under subsection (b)(4) is
41 due, and the inspection fees required under this chapter are payable,
42 semiannually on the last day of the month following the end of the
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

16
1 semiannual period. The first half reporting period ends June 30 and the
2 second half reporting period ends December 31.
3 SECTION 23. IC 15-15-1-34.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
4 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
5 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 34.5. (a) The state seed
6 commissioner shall charge the amount set forth in this section.
7 (b) A person who distributes agricultural seed or vegetable seed
8 in Indiana may apply to the state seed commissioner for a permit
9 to use the person's own labeling, report the quantity of seed sold,
10 and pay the inspection fee on the basis of the report. Subject to
11 subsection (i), the inspection fee is the following:
12 (1) Thirty cents ($0.30) per one hundred (100) pounds of
13 alfalfa, clover, vegetable, grass seed, and mixtures of the
14 seeds, with a minimum payment of seven and one-half cents
15 ($0.075) for each package or container weighing more than
16 one (1) pound.
17 (2) Fifteen cents ($0.15) per one hundred (100) pounds of all
18 agricultural seed other than seeds described in subdivision (1),
19 with a minimum payment of three and three-fourths cents
20 ($0.0375) for each package or container weighing more than
21 one (1) pound.
22 (c) A person who distributes vegetable seeds in:
23 (1) packets as prepared for use in home gardens or household
24 plantings; or
25 (2) preplanted containers, mats, tapes, or other planting
26 devices;
27 in containers of not more than one (1) pound shall pay three dollars
28 ($3) for each retail location offering the assortments or display
29 units of seed for sale in Indiana.
30 (d) When applying for a permit under subsection (c), the
31 distributor must agree to the following:
32 (1) Label the seed with the information required by law.
33 (2) Keep the records the state seed commissioner considers
34 necessary to indicate accurately the number and size of
35 containers of each kind of agricultural seed and vegetable
36 seed distributed and the quantity of the seed distributed in
37 bulk.
38 (3) Grant the state seed commissioner or the state seed
39 commissioner's authorized representative permission to
40 examine the records described in subdivision (2) and verify
41 the statement of quantity of seed distributed.
42 (4) Report under oath to the state seed commissioner on forms
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

17
1 furnished by the state seed commissioner the quantity of
2 agricultural seed and vegetable seed sold during the period
3 covered.
4 (e) The state seed commissioner may grant a permit under
5 subsection (b) if the state seed commissioner determines that the
6 applicant's proposed report of the quality of agricultural seed and
7 vegetable seed sold will lead to efficient enforcement of this
8 chapter. The state seed commissioner may revoke the permit at any
9 time if it appears to the state seed commissioner that the
10 distributor is not complying with the agreement described in
11 subsection (d).
12 (f) Subject to subsection (j), the report required under
13 subsection (d)(4) must be filed and inspection fees must be paid
14 semiannually as follows:
15 (1) For the first half semiannual reporting period beginning
16 January 1 and ending June 30, not later than July 31.
17 (2) For the second half semiannual reporting period beginning
18 July 1 and ending December 31, not later than January 31.
19 (g) If the:
20 (1) report is not filed and the inspection fee not paid not more
21 than fifteen (15) days following the due date;
22 (2) report of quantity sold is false; or
23 (3) labeling requirements of this chapter have not been
24 complied with;
25 the state seed commissioner may revoke the distributor's permit.
26 (h) If the report is not filed and the inspection fee not paid on
27 the sixteenth day following the due date described in subsection (f),
28 a penalty must be assessed in the amount of:
29 (1) fifty dollars ($50); or
30 (2) ten percent (10%) of the amount due;
31 whichever is greater, in addition to the amount due.
32 (i) If a report is required under this section, the minimum
33 inspection fee is ten dollars ($10) per reporting period.
34 (j) An inspection fee is not required to be paid on seed supplied
35 to a wholesaler whose predominant business is to supply other
36 distributors rather than consumers of seed. Seeds distributed
37 under all other conditions (except those specifically exempted in
38 section 31 of this chapter) must be completely labeled and the
39 inspection fee must be paid for the seeds when distributed. The
40 inspection fee is not required to be paid more than once on any
41 shipment of seed.
42 (k) Two (2) times each year the state seed commissioner shall
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

18
1 issue a credit to any distributor of seed for the inspection fee paid
2 to the distributor's supplier on seed subsequently sold to a
3 wholesaler.
4 SECTION 24. IC 15-15-1-36, AS ADDED BY P.L.2-2008,
5 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
6 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 36. (a) Each person whose name appears on the
7 label as distributing agricultural seed or vegetable seed subject to this
8 chapter shall do the following:
9 (1) Keep for two (2) years complete records of each lot of
10 agricultural seed or vegetable seed distributed.
11 (2) Keep for one (1) year a file sample of each lot of seed that is
12 distributed after final disposition of the lot.
13 (b) All records and samples relating to the shipments involved must
14 be accessible for inspection by the state seed commissioner or the state
15 seed commissioner's agent during customary business hours.
16 (c) The permit holder shall report the quantities of agricultural
17 seed and vegetable seed on forms furnished to the permit holder by
18 the state seed commissioner semiannually. The quantities must be
19 reported according to kind of seed as designated on the report
20 form.
21 SECTION 25. IC 15-15-1-38, AS ADDED BY P.L.2-2008,
22 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
23 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 38. (a) The state seed commissioner may file an
24 action for the seizure of any lot of agricultural seed or vegetable seed
25 that violates this chapter.
26 (b) An action filed under this section must be filed in a court with
27 jurisdiction in the locality in which the seed is located.
28 (c) If the court finds the seed to be in violation of this chapter and
29 orders the condemnation of the seed, the seed shall be denatured,
30 processed, destroyed, relabeled, or disposed of in compliance with
31 Indiana law. The court may not order the disposition of the seed unless
32 the claimant is given an opportunity to apply to the court for release of
33 the seed or permission to process or relabel the seed to bring it into
34 compliance with this chapter.
35 SECTION 26. IC 15-15-1-40, AS AMENDED BY P.L.17-2014,
36 SECTION 1, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
37 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 40. A person may not distribute agricultural seed
38 or vegetable seed within Indiana if any of the following apply:
39 (1) If the test to determine the percentage of germination (as
40 defined by rule adopted under section 28 of this chapter) required
41 by sections 32 and 33 of this chapter has not been completed
42 within a twelve (12) month period, not including the calendar
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

19
1 month in which the test was completed immediately before
2 distribution. However, the state seed commissioner may by rule
3 designate:
4 (A) a shorter period for a kind of agricultural seed or vegetable
5 seed that the state seed commissioner finds under ordinary
6 conditions of handling will not maintain, during a twelve (12)
7 month period, a germination within the established tolerance
8 limits; or
9 (B) a longer period for a kind of agricultural seed or vegetable
10 seed that is packaged in such container materials and under
11 such conditions prescribed by the state seed commissioner that
12 the state seed commissioner finds will, during the longer
13 period, maintain the viability of the seed under ordinary
14 conditions of handling.
15 (2) If the seed is not labeled in accordance with this chapter.
16 (3) If the seed carries labeling that is false or misleading in any
17 particular.
18 (4) If the seed contains or consists of prohibited noxious weed
19 seed.
20 (5) If the seed consists of or contains restricted noxious weed seed
21 in excess of one-fourth of one percent (0.25%). If less than
22 one-fourth of one percent (0.25%) of weed seed by weight is
23 present, the number per pound must be declared on the labeling.
24 (6) If the seed contains more than two and one-half percent
25 (2.5%) of all weed seed.
26 (7) If the seed is represented to be "certified seed", "registered
27 seed", or "foundation seed", the seed has not been produced and
28 labeled in accordance with the procedures and in compliance with
29 rules of an official or officially recognized seed certification or
30 registration agency.
31 (8) If the inoculant applied to pre-inoculated seed is ineffective as
32 determined by standards established by rule.
33 SECTION 27. IC 15-15-1-41, AS AMENDED BY P.L.75-2010,
34 SECTION 9, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
35 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 41. A person may not do any of the following:
36 (1) Detach, alter, deface, or destroy any label provided for in this
37 chapter or the rules adopted under this chapter.
38 (2) Alter or substitute seed in a manner that may defeat the
39 purpose of this chapter.
40 (3) Disseminate false or misleading advertisements concerning
41 agricultural seed or vegetable seed.
42 (4) Hinder or obstruct in any way an authorized person in the
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

20
1 performance of the person's duties under this chapter.
2 (5) Fail to comply with a stop sale order issued under section 27
3 of this chapter.
4 (6) Use the word:
5 (A) "trace" as a substitute for any statement required by this
6 chapter; or
7 (B) "type" in any labeling in connection with the name of any
8 seed variety.
9 (7) Use a state seed commissioner tag or label more than once.
10 (8) Sell grain or other seed that has been treated to any person for
11 any purpose unless the grain or seed is clearly labeled as required
12 in sections 32 and 33 of this chapter.
13 (9) Distribute seed colored so that it does not contrast with the
14 natural color of the seed.
15 (10) Distribute noxious weed seed without a special use permit
16 issued by the seed commissioner under section 27(b)(17) of this
17 chapter.
18 (11) Assign the same brand designation to more than one (1)
19 variety or blend of the same kind of seed, if not sold by variety
20 name.
21 (12) Use relabeling stickers unless the relabeling stickers state:
22 (A) both the calendar month and year the germination test was
23 completed and the sell-by date, as required under sections
24 31.5, 32, and 33 of this chapter; and
25 (B) the lot number that matches the existing original lot
26 number.
27 (13) Relabel a seed lot using stickers more than once.
28 SECTION 28. IC 15-15-1-44 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
29 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
30 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 44. (a) In order to secure a
31 representative sample, equal portions must be taken from evenly
32 distributed parts of the quantity of seed or screenings to be
33 sampled. Access must be available to all parts of the quantity of
34 seed. When more than one (1) trierful of seed is drawn from a bag,
35 different paths through the bag must be followed. When more than
36 one (1) handful is taken from a bag, the handfuls must be taken
37 from well-separated points.
38 (b) Free flowing seeds must be sampled as follows:
39 (1) For free flowing seed in bags or bulk, a probe or trier must
40 be used.
41 (2) For small free flowing seed in bags, a probe or trier long
42 enough to sample all portions of the bag must be used.
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

21
1 (c) Non-free flowing seed, including certain grass seed or
2 uncleaned seed or screenings, that is difficult to sample with a
3 probe or trier must be sampled by inserting the hand into the bulk
4 and withdrawing representative portions. The hand is inserted in
5 an open position and the fingers are held closely together while the
6 hand is being inserted and the portion withdrawn.
7 (d) As the seed or screenings are sampled, the person taking the
8 sample shall examine each portion of the sample. If the sample
9 appears to lack uniformity, the portions may not be combined into
10 a composite sample but must be retained as separate samples or
11 combined to form individual container samples to determine if a
12 lack of uniformity may exist.
13 (e) If the portions appear to be uniform, the portions must be
14 combined to form a composite sample.
15 SECTION 29. IC 15-15-1-45 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
16 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
17 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 45. Bulk seed or screenings must
18 be sampled by inserting a long probe or inserting the hand into the
19 bulk as circumstances require in at least seven (7) uniformly
20 distributed parts of the quantity being sampled. At least as many
21 trierfuls or handfuls must be taken as the minimum which would
22 be required for the same quantity of seed or screenings in bags of
23 a size customarily used for the seed or screenings.
24 SECTION 30. IC 15-15-1-46 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
25 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
26 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 46. (a) For lots of six (6) bags or
27 less, each bag must be sampled. A total of at least five (5) trierfuls
28 must be taken.
29 (b) For lots of more than six (6) bags, five (5) bags plus at least
30 ten percent (10%) of the number of bags in the lots must be
31 sampled (rounding off numbers with decimals to the nearest whole
32 number, raising five-tenths (0.5) to the next whole number).
33 Regardless of the lot size, it is not necessary that more than thirty
34 (30) bags be sampled.
35 (c) Samples must be drawn from unopened bags except under
36 circumstances where the identity of the seed has been preserved.
37 SECTION 31. IC 15-15-1-47 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
38 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
39 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 47. In sampling seed in a small
40 container where it is not practical to sample as required by section
41 46 of this chapter, a portion of one (1) unopened container or one
42 (1) or more entire unopened containers may be taken to supply a
2026 IN 1192—LS 6703/DI 148

22
1 minimum size sample.
